China Stocks: ICBC, China Vanke, Poly, Zhongjin Gold, CSR

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-02-18T03:08:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-18/china-stocks-icbc-china-vanke-poly-zhongjin-gold-csr.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 10:35 a.m.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, lost 11.6, or 0.4 percent, to 2,915.37.
The  CSI 300 Index  slid 0.4 percent to 3,233.29.  Banks: China’s banking regulator ordered the country’s
lenders to reduce their reliance on the debt grades given to
companies by external ratings firms and focus more on their own
internal assessments to avoid systemic risks, according to a
statement published by the China Banking Regulatory Commission
after the markets closed yesterday.    Industrial & Commercial Bank of China  Ltd. (601398 CH) fell
0.5 percent to 4.31 yuan.  Bank of China Ltd . (601988 CH) dropped
0.6 at 3.27 yuan.  Developers: China Vanke Co. (000002 CH) added 0.4 percent
to 8.40 yuan, the first increase in four days. Poly Real Estate
Group Co. (600048 CH) gained 1.2 percent to 13.12 yuan.  Beijing’s new home prices rose 6.8 percent in January from
a year earlier, the statistics bureau said on its website today.
New home prices in  Shanghai  rose 1.5 percent last month compared
with a year ago, the statement said.  Gold producers: Zhongjin Gold Co. (600489 CH) climbed 1.9
percent to 36.65 yuan. Shandong Gold Mining Co. (600547 CH)
added 2.1 percent to 48.89 yuan.  China’s gold investment demand will grow 40 percent to 50
percent this year, Wang Lixin, the China representative for the
World Gold Council, said late yesterday. The country’s jewelry
demand will expand by 8 percent to 10 percent this year, he said.  CSR Corp. (601766 CH), China’s biggest train maker, jumped
2.6 percent to 8.76 yuan, set for the highest close since Feb. 9.
The company has entered into contracts valued at a combined 7.5
billion yuan.  --Irene Shen, Chua Baizhen in Beijing. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
